                        <section class="pmc-journal-banner text-center line-height-none" aria-label="Journal banner"><img src="https://cdn.ncbi.nlm.nih.gov/pmc/banners/logo-procamia.gif" alt="AMIA Annual Symposium Proceedings logo" usemap="#pmc-banner-imagemap" width="500" height="75"><map name="pmc-banner-imagemap"><area alt="Link to AMIA Annual Symposium Proceedings" title="Link to AMIA Annual Symposium Proceedings" shape="default" href="https://knowledge.amia.org/all-proceedings" target="_blank" rel="noopener noreferrer"></map></section><article lang="en"><section aria-label="Article citation and metadata"><section class="pmc-layout__citation font-secondary font-xs"><div>
<div class="display-inline-block"><button type="button" class="cursor-pointer text-no-underline bg-transparent border-0 padding-0 text-left margin-0 text-normal text-primary" aria-controls="journal_context_menu">AMIA Annu Symp Proc</button></div>. 2005;2005:106–110.</div>
<nav id="journal_context_menu" hidden="hidden"><ul class="menu-list font-family-ui" role="menu">
<li role="presentation"><a href='https://pmc.ncbi.nlm.nih.gov/search/?term="AMIA%20Annu%20Symp%20Proc"[jour]' class="usa-link" role="menuitem">Search in PMC</a></li>
<li role="presentation"><a href='https://pubmed.ncbi.nlm.nih.gov/?term="AMIA%20Annu%20Symp%20Proc"[jour]' lang="en" class="usa-link" role="menuitem">Search in PubMed</a></li>
<li role="presentation"><a href='https://www.ncbi.nlm.nih.gov/nlmcatalog?term="AMIA%20Annu%20Symp%20Proc"[Title%20Abbreviation]' class="usa-link" role="menuitem">View in NLM Catalog</a></li>
<li role="presentation"><a href='?term="AMIA%20Annu%20Symp%20Proc"[jour]' class="usa-link" role="menuitem" data-add-to-search="true">Add to search</a></li>
</ul></nav></section><section class="front-matter"><div class="ameta p font-secondary font-xs">
<hgroup><h1>Mining a clinical data warehouse to discover disease-finding associations
using co-occurrence statistics</h1></hgroup><div class="cg p">
<a href='https://pubmed.ncbi.nlm.nih.gov/?term="Cao%20H"[Author]' class="usa-link" aria-describedby="id1"><span class="name western">Hui Cao</span></a><div hidden="hidden" id="id1">
<h3>
<span class="name western">Hui Cao</span>, <span class="degrees">MD, MPhil</span>
</h3>
<div class="p">
<sup>a</sup> Department of Biomedical Informatics, Columbia University, New York, NY</div>
<div class="p">Find articles by <a href='https://pubmed.ncbi.nlm.nih.gov/?term="Cao%20H"[Author]' class="usa-link"><span class="name western">Hui Cao</span></a>
</div>
</div>
<sup>a</sup>, <a href='https://pubmed.ncbi.nlm.nih.gov/?term="Markatou%20M"[Author]' class="usa-link" aria-describedby="id2"><span class="name western">Marianthi Markatou</span></a><div hidden="hidden" id="id2">
<h3>
<span class="name western">Marianthi Markatou</span>, <span class="degrees">PhD</span>
</h3>
<div class="p">
<sup>b</sup> Department of Biostatistics, Columbia University, New York, NY</div>
<div class="p">Find articles by <a href='https://pubmed.ncbi.nlm.nih.gov/?term="Markatou%20M"[Author]' class="usa-link"><span class="name western">Marianthi Markatou</span></a>
</div>
</div>
<sup>b</sup>, <a href='https://pubmed.ncbi.nlm.nih.gov/?term="Melton%20GB"[Author]' class="usa-link" aria-describedby="id3"><span class="name western">Genevieve B Melton</span></a><div hidden="hidden" id="id3">
<h3>
<span class="name western">Genevieve B Melton</span>, <span class="degrees">MD</span>
</h3>
<div class="p">
<sup>a</sup> Department of Biomedical Informatics, Columbia University, New York, NY</div>
<div class="p">Find articles by <a href='https://pubmed.ncbi.nlm.nih.gov/?term="Melton%20GB"[Author]' class="usa-link"><span class="name western">Genevieve B Melton</span></a>
</div>
</div>
<sup>a</sup>, <a href='https://pubmed.ncbi.nlm.nih.gov/?term="Chiang%20MF"[Author]' class="usa-link" aria-describedby="id4"><span class="name western">Michael F Chiang</span></a><div hidden="hidden" id="id4">
<h3>
<span class="name western">Michael F Chiang</span>, <span class="degrees">MD, MA</span>
</h3>
<div class="p">
<sup>a</sup> Department of Biomedical Informatics, Columbia University, New York, NY</div>
<div class="p">Find articles by <a href='https://pubmed.ncbi.nlm.nih.gov/?term="Chiang%20MF"[Author]' class="usa-link"><span class="name western">Michael F Chiang</span></a>
</div>
</div>
<sup>a</sup>, <a href='https://pubmed.ncbi.nlm.nih.gov/?term="Hripcsak%20G"[Author]' class="usa-link" aria-describedby="id5"><span class="name western">George Hripcsak</span></a><div hidden="hidden" id="id5">
<h3>
<span class="name western">George Hripcsak</span>, <span class="degrees">MD, MS</span>
</h3>
<div class="p">
<sup>a</sup> Department of Biomedical Informatics, Columbia University, New York, NY</div>
<div class="p">Find articles by <a href='https://pubmed.ncbi.nlm.nih.gov/?term="Hripcsak%20G"[Author]' class="usa-link"><span class="name western">George Hripcsak</span></a>
</div>
</div>
<sup>a</sup>
</div>
<ul class="d-buttons inline-list">
<li><button class="d-button" aria-controls="aip_a" aria-expanded="false">Author information</button></li>
<li><button class="d-button" aria-controls="clp_a" aria-expanded="false">Copyright and License information</button></li>
</ul>
<div class="d-panels font-secondary-light">
<div id="aip_a" class="d-panel p" style="display: none">
<div class="p" id="af1-amia2005_0106">
<sup>a</sup> Department of Biomedical Informatics, Columbia University, New York, NY</div>
<div id="af2-amia2005_0106">
<sup>b</sup> Department of Biostatistics, Columbia University, New York, NY</div>
</div>
<div id="clp_a" class="d-panel p" style="display: none">
<div>This is an Open Access article: verbatim copying and redistribution of
this article are permitted in all media for any purpose</div>
<div class="p"><a href="/about/copyright/" class="usa-link">PMC Copyright notice</a></div>
</div>
</div>
<div>PMCID: PMC1560759  PMID: <a href="https://pubmed.ncbi.nlm.nih.gov/16779011/" class="usa-link">16779011</a>
</div>
</div></section></section><section aria-label="Article content"><section class="body main-article-body"><section class="abstract" id="abstract1"><h2>Abstract</h2>
<p>This paper applies co-occurrence statistics to discover disease-finding
associations in a clinical data warehouse. We used two methods, χ<sup>2</sup> statistics and the proportion confidence interval (PCI) method, to measure
the dependence of pairs of diseases and findings, and then used heuristic
cutoff values for association selection. An intrinsic evaluation
showed that 94 percent of disease-finding associations obtained by χ<sup>2</sup> statistics and 76.8 percent obtained by the PCI method were true associations. The
selected associations were used to construct knowledge bases
of disease-finding relations (KB-χ<sup>2</sup>, KB-PCI). An extrinsic evaluation showed that both KB-χ<sup>2</sup> and KB-PCI could assist in eliminating clinically non-informative and
redundant findings from problem lists generated by our automated problem
list summarization system.</p></section><section id="sec1"><h2 class="pmc_sec_title">1. Introduction</h2>
<p>Problem-centered medical records enable better electronic medical record (EMR)-based
information transactions among healthcare providers [<a href="#b1-amia2005_0106" class="usa-link" aria-describedby="b1-amia2005_0106">1</a>–<a href="#b2-amia2005_0106" class="usa-link" aria-describedby="b2-amia2005_0106">2</a>]. One of the essential keys to realizing the problem-centered
EMR is the ability to automatically generate a medical problem list, defined
as a list of all major active and inactive medical problems. The
major weakness of current automated problem list generators is that
they lack sufficient knowledge to interpret problems in the list [<a href="#b3-amia2005_0106" class="usa-link" aria-describedby="b3-amia2005_0106">3</a>]. Therefore, the generated lists are just lists of diagnoses, symptoms
and signs. Ideally, problem lists should also display the relations
among these problems. To achieve this goal, automated problem list
summarization systems need to be equipped with knowledge of associations
between diseases and findings. Manually created knowledge bases
ensure a certain level of quality, but they require a substantial amount
of human labor. Consequently, computerized methods are needed to create
knowledge bases of disease-finding associations that can be used
for automated problem list generation.</p>
<p>Co-occurrence statistics have proven very effective in discovering associations
between concepts. One important example comes from information
retrieval. As early as the late 1950s, statistical co-occurrence was
explored as a means of enlarging and sharpening literature searches by
several researchers [<a href="#b4-amia2005_0106" class="usa-link" aria-describedby="b4-amia2005_0106">4</a>]. Another familiar example is computational linguistics, in which
co-occurrence statistics were applied for word sense disambiguation, word
clustering and lexicon construction [<a href="#b5-amia2005_0106" class="usa-link" aria-describedby="b5-amia2005_0106">5</a>]. Since the 1990s, co-occurrence statistics have also been widely
used in synonym mining and word-to-word translation [<a href="#b6-amia2005_0106" class="usa-link" aria-describedby="b6-amia2005_0106">6</a>].</p>
<p>The idea for using co-occurrence statistics began with the hypothesis that
a disease and an associated finding are more likely to appear together
than random combinations of diseases and findings. Manning and Schütze
distinguished between co-occurrence and collocation [<a href="#b7-amia2005_0106" class="usa-link" aria-describedby="b7-amia2005_0106">7</a>]: “collocation” refers to “grammatically
bound elements that occur in a particular order”, while “co-occurrence” refers to “the more general phenomenon
of words that are likely to be used in the same context”. Because
neither grammatical order nor the distance between two terms
in a text is relevant to the association between a disease and a finding, we
consider only the co-occurrence of two terms, rather than their
collocation or distance within a text.</p>
<p>In our previous problem list project, we built a summarization system that
automatically produced a ranked lifetime problem list from a patient’s
entire set of discharge summaries [<a href="#b3-amia2005_0106" class="usa-link" aria-describedby="b3-amia2005_0106">3</a>]. System evaluation compared system-generated problem lists with
expert-generated problem lists and revealed two interesting features. First, experts
tended to list major underlying problems initially and
then organize other related problems as a subset of the major underlying
problems. For example, a patient with coronary artery disease and
a history of heart bypass surgery, heart attack, and persistent unstable
angina had his problems described by experts as follows:</p>
<p>Coronary Artery Disease</p>
<p>(Myocardial Infarction, Coronary Artery Bypass Grafting Surgery, now with
persistent unstable angina)</p>
<p>Second, the experts eliminated two types of findings: (1) very common findings, such
as pain and fever, which were felt to be clinically non-informative (2) findings
that could be easily explained by the patient’s
underlying diseases, such as chest pain in a myocardial infarction
patient, which were felt to be redundant.</p>
<p>The goal of this study is to mine a clinical data warehouse in order to
discover disease-finding associations that our automated problem list
summarization system could use to (1) remove redundant and clinically
non-informative findings and (2) link findings with associated diseases. We
will describe the statistical methods developed for this purpose, followed
by the implementation and evaluation of this system.</p></section><section id="sec2"><h2 class="pmc_sec_title">2. Statistical methodology development</h2>
<section id="sec3"><h3 class="pmc_sec_title">2.1 χ<sup>2</sup> statistics and volume tests</h3>
<p>The essence of statistical analysis on the cooccurrence data was to compute
the association strength between a disease and finding pair by comparing
their expected and observed frequencies. The χ<sup>2</sup> statistic is a classical method that is widely used for this type of analysis. The χ<sup>2</sup> test compares the observed frequencies with the frequencies expected for
independence. If the difference between observed and expected frequencies
is large, then the null hypothesis of independence can be rejected. We
have a large sample size (18,432 discharge summaries), which offers
enough power for the test to detect small difference between observed
and expected frequencies even though the overall magnitude of difference
is negligible. Consequently, nearly half of the disease-finding
pairs in the data reject the null hypothesis even though the pairs
are not associated in medicine. For all the 2 × 2 tables drawn
from the same sample, the higher the χ<sup>2</sup> value the greater the magnitude of the dependence. Therefore, we used
a heuristic approach. We sorted all co-occurrence pairs by their χ<sup>2</sup> values, reviewed the pairs and then decided on a high cutoff of 100 to
select the most significant ones as disease-finding associations.</p>
<p>We then used volume tests to determine the appropriateness of our heuristic
cutoff. With volume tests, the distribution of χ<sup>2</sup> is considered under a uniform distribution, in which every possible contingency
table of the given dimension and sample size receives equal
probability. The idea of volume tests is to look among all the possible
contingency tables with the same number of rows and columns with the
observed table and evaluate which proportion leads to χ<sup>2</sup> statistics with values smaller than or equal to the recorded one [<a href="#b8-amia2005_0106" class="usa-link" aria-describedby="b8-amia2005_0106">8</a>]. In practice, the proportion is the ratio of volumes of a set
of points with a χ<sup>2</sup> value less than or equal to the observed value and the entire simplex
of 2 × 2 tables, and can be interpreted as a distance from independence. In
volume tests, the adjustment for the <em>p</em> value is calculated using the following formula:</p>
<table class="disp-formula p" id="FD1"><tr><td class="formula"><math id="M1" display="block" overflow="linebreak"><mrow><mi>ε</mi><mo stretchy="false">(</mo><msup><mrow><mi>x</mi></mrow><mn>2</mn></msup><mo stretchy="false">)</mo><mo>=</mo><mfrac><mrow><msup><mrow><mrow><mo stretchy="false">(</mo><mi>π</mi><mo>×</mo><mfrac><mrow><msup><mrow><mi>χ</mi></mrow><mn>2</mn></msup></mrow><mi>n</mi></mfrac><mo stretchy="false">)</mo></mrow></mrow><mrow><mfrac><mi>D</mi><mn>2</mn></mfrac></mrow></msup><msub><mrow><mi>C</mi></mrow><mrow><mi>I</mi><mo>,</mo><mi>J</mi></mrow></msub><mo stretchy="false">[</mo><mfrac><mrow><msqrt><mrow><mi>I</mi><mi>J</mi></mrow></msqrt></mrow><mrow><mi>τ</mi><mo stretchy="false">(</mo><mi>I</mi><mi>J</mi><mo stretchy="false">)</mo></mrow></mfrac><mo stretchy="false">]</mo><mo>×</mo><mfrac><mrow><msup><mrow><mi>n</mi></mrow><mrow><mi>I</mi><mi>J</mi><mo>-</mo><mn>1</mn></mrow></msup></mrow><mrow><msqrt><mrow><mi>I</mi><mi>J</mi></mrow></msqrt></mrow></mfrac></mrow><mrow><mrow><mo>(</mo><mrow><mtable><mtr><mtd><mrow><mi>n</mi><mo>+</mo><mi>I</mi><mi>J</mi><mo>-</mo><mn>1</mn></mrow></mtd></mtr><mtr><mtd><mrow><mi>I</mi><mi>J</mi><mo>-</mo><mn>1</mn></mrow></mtd></mtr></mtable></mrow><mo>)</mo></mrow></mrow></mfrac></mrow></math></td></tr></table>
<p>where <em>n</em> is the total cases in the sample, <em>D</em> is the degree of freedom, <em>I</em> is the number of rows, and <em>J</em> is the number of columns.</p>
<p>From the standpoint of statistics, the 85<sup>th</sup> percentile of the distribution of <em>p</em> values from volume tests can be empirically set as the cutoff value. Our
cutoff of 100, which corresponds to a value of 0.1362 in volume tests, is
the 96<sup>th</sup> percentile and represents a much stricter cutoff value than the 85<sup>th</sup> percentile and an appropriate level to be used for association selection.</p></section><section id="sec4"><h3 class="pmc_sec_title">2.2 Confidence interval of a proportion</h3>
<p>Our challenge was to develop a methodology that would eliminate redundant
findings in the same manner that a physician would. Intuitively, if
a finding often presents with a disease, it does not provide much information
about the disease and hence it is unnecessary to put this finding
in a problem list. The proportion of a finding in the sample disease
population can be calculated using our co-occurrence data. Due to
the existence of rare diseases, instead of using the proportion directly, we
calculated its 95% confidence interval (CI) and used the
lower limit. We experimented with different cutoff values between 0.1 and 0.4 in
a small training set until we decided on a value of 0.15, which
allowed us to achieve adequate levels for both sensitivity and
specificity.</p></section></section><section id="sec5"><h2 class="pmc_sec_title">3. Methods</h2>
<section id="sec6"><h3 class="pmc_sec_title">3.1 Definition of disease-finding co-occurrence</h3>
<p>For this study, we defined a disease-finding co-occurrence in the following
way: For a discharge summary <em>s</em> in which a set of diseases D(<em>s</em>) and a set of findings F(<em>s</em>) present, a disease <em>d</em> and a finding <em>f</em> are said to co-occur in <em>s</em> if <em>d</em> ∈ D(<em>s</em>) and <em>f</em> ∈ F(<em>s</em>). All disease-findings co-occurrence pairs can be expressed for a corpus
as S = {(d<sub>i</sub> f<sub>j</sub>), r<sub>(</sub>d<sub>i</sub> f<sub>j )</sub>, fr (d<sub>i</sub>), fr (f<sub>j</sub>)}, where (d<sub>i</sub>, f<sub>j</sub>) refers to the co-occurrence of disease d<sub>i</sub> and finding f<sub>j</sub>, r<sub>(</sub>d<sub>i</sub> f<sub>j )</sub> is the co-occurrence frequency of (d<sub>i</sub> f<sub>j</sub>) (i.e., the number of discharge summaries in which d<sub>i</sub> and f<sub>j</sub> co-occur), fr (d<sub>i</sub>) is the frequency of d<sub>i</sub>, and fr (f<sub>j</sub>) is the frequency of f<sub>j</sub>.</p></section><section id="sec7"><h3 class="pmc_sec_title">3.2 Corpus preparation, text processing and data collection</h3>
<p>All unique discharge summaries dictated in the year 2000 were collected
from our data warehouse, and then parsed and transformed to textual knowledge
representation structures in extended markup language (XML) format
by the Medical Language Extraction and Encoding System (MedLEE), a
Natural Language Processing (NLP) system in use at Columbia University
Medical Center (CUMC) [<a href="#b9-amia2005_0106" class="usa-link" aria-describedby="b9-amia2005_0106">9</a>]. A Perl script performed two tasks on the transformed data: (1) reduce
redundant terms by merging synonyms to one concept and (2) convert
each discharge summary to two vectors: a disease vector (a list
of disease terms present in the discharge summary) and a finding vector (a
list of finding terms present in the discharge summary). The co-occurrences
of diseases in the disease vector and findings in the finding
vector were found for each discharge summary and all disease-finding
pairs were collected across all discharge summaries. All co-occurrence
pairs that had a frequency of less than 2 were excluded because they
do not yield significant statistical results.</p></section><section id="sec8"><h3 class="pmc_sec_title">3.3 Statistical measurement of dependence for association selection</h3>
<p>We calculated the χ<sup>2</sup> value for each disease-finding co-occurrence pair. All co-occurrence pairs
with a χ<sup>2</sup> value greater than the heuristic cutoff of 100 were selected as positive
associations. We used these positive associations to construct our
first knowledge base of disease-finding associations (KB-χ<sup>2</sup>).</p>
<p>For each co-occurrence pair (d<sub>i</sub>, f<sub>j</sub>), we calculated the proportion of f<sub>j</sub> in the d<sub>i</sub> population. We assumed that all cases were mutually independent and that
the probability of a specific finding occurrence remained constant
from one case to the next. Our sample size was large enough to permit
using the normal approximation to calculate a 95% CI:</p>
<table class="disp-formula p" id="FD2"><tr><td class="formula"><math id="M2" display="block" overflow="linebreak"><mrow><mi>C</mi><mi>I</mi><mo>=</mo><mstyle scriptlevel="1"><mfrac><mi>r</mi><mi>n</mi></mfrac></mstyle><mo>±</mo><msub><mrow><mi>x</mi></mrow><mrow><mn>1</mn><mo>-</mo><mfrac><mi>α</mi><mn>2</mn></mfrac></mrow></msub><msqrt><mrow><mfrac><mrow><mi>r</mi><mo>×</mo><mo stretchy="false">(</mo><mi>n</mi><mo>-</mo><mi>r</mi><mo stretchy="false">)</mo></mrow><mrow><msup><mrow><mi>n</mi></mrow><mn>3</mn></msup></mrow></mfrac></mrow></msqrt></mrow></math></td></tr></table>
<p>where <em>r</em> is the frequency of f<sub>j</sub> in the d<sub>i</sub> population, <em>n</em> is the total number of cases in the d<sub>i</sub> population, and <em>x</em><sub>1−α/2</sub> is the quantile of a normally distributed random variable. For example, if α is 0.05, then
the confidence coefficient (1 – α) is 0.95 and
hence <em>x</em><sub>1−α/2</sub> is 1.96.</p>
<p>For each pair (d<sub>i</sub>, f<sub>j</sub>), if the lower limit of the f<sub>j</sub> proportion in d<sub>i</sub> was greater than the cutoff of 0.15, the pair was selected as a positive
association. All pairs selected were then used to construct our second
knowledge base (KB-PCI).</p>
<p>Both KB-χ<sup>2</sup> and KB-PCI were implemented as hash tables. Each entry in the hash tables
had the finding as the key and the list of associated diseases as
the value.</p></section></section><section id="sec9"><h2 class="pmc_sec_title">3. 3 Evaluation of KB-χ<sup>2</sup> and KB-PCI</h2>
<p>To evaluate our two knowledge bases, we applied two evaluation strategies: intrinsic
evaluation, in which experts directly judged the obtained
associations, and extrinsic evaluation, in which the usefulness of the
knowledge bases in eliminating findings was evaluated.</p>
<p>Before performing the intrinsic evaluation, we conducted a validity study. Two
hundred ninety-nine associations were randomly selected from the
two knowledge bases. Two raters (HC, GM) examined them and gave each
association a score using the scale described in <a href="#t1-amia2005_0106" class="usa-link">Table 1</a>.</p>
<section class="tw xbox font-sm" id="t1-amia2005_0106"><h3 class="obj_head">Table 1.</h3>
<div class="caption p"><p>The intrinsic evaluation scale</p></div>
<div class="tbl-box p" tabindex="0"><table class="content" frame="hsides" rules="groups">
<thead><tr>
<th align="left" rowspan="1" colspan="1">Score</th>
<th align="left" rowspan="1" colspan="1">Interpretation</th>
<th align="left" rowspan="1" colspan="1">Example</th>
</tr></thead>
<tbody>
<tr>
<td align="left" rowspan="1" colspan="1">1</td>
<td align="left" rowspan="1" colspan="1">direct association</td>
<td align="left" rowspan="1" colspan="1">“gastritis” and “melena”</td>
</tr>
<tr>
<td align="left" rowspan="1" colspan="1">2</td>
<td align="left" rowspan="1" colspan="1">indirect association</td>
<td align="left" rowspan="1" colspan="1">“liver cirrhosis” and “hematemesis”</td>
</tr>
<tr>
<td align="left" rowspan="1" colspan="1">3</td>
<td align="left" rowspan="1" colspan="1">Non-association</td>
<td align="left" rowspan="1" colspan="1">“acute kidney failure” and “diarrhea”</td>
</tr>
</tbody>
</table></div>
<div class="p text-right font-secondary"><a href="table/t1-amia2005_0106/" class="usa-link" target="_blank" rel="noopener noreferrer">Open in a new tab</a></div>
<div class="tw-foot p"><div class="fn" id="tfn1-amia2005_0535"><p>One rater (HC) then reviewed and graded all the associations using the
same scale.</p></div></div></section><p>The extrinsic evaluation design is summarized in <a href="#f1-amia2005_0106" class="usa-link">Figure 1</a>. 27 cases were randomly selected from the clinical data warehouse. For
each case, first we used our automated summarization system to generate
a preliminary problem list that consisted of a disease list and a finding
list. We then built two interpreters, one of which used KB-χ<sup>2</sup>, while the other one used KB-PCI. The interpreters eliminated findings
that were found to be associated with the diseases present in the preliminary
problem list. The 27 preliminary problem lists were also presented
to two raters (GBM, MFC). They performed the same task, eliminating
the findings that they felt did not need to appear in the problem
lists.</p>
<figure class="fig xbox font-sm" id="f1-amia2005_0106"><h3 class="obj_head">Figure 1.</h3>
<p class="img-box line-height-none margin-x-neg-2 tablet:margin-x-0 text-center"><a class="tileshop" target="_blank" href="https://www.ncbi.nlm.nih.gov/core/lw/2.0/html/tileshop_pmc/tileshop_pmc_inline.html?title=Click%20on%20image%20to%20zoom&amp;p=PMC3&amp;id=1560759_amia2005_0106f1.jpg"><img class="graphic zoom-in" src="https://cdn.ncbi.nlm.nih.gov/pmc/blobs/06e8/1560759/e5023da4816a/amia2005_0106f1.jpg" loading="lazy" height="447" width="474" alt="Figure 1"></a></p>
<div class="p text-right font-secondary"><a href="figure/f1-amia2005_0106/" class="usa-link" target="_blank" rel="noopener noreferrer">Open in a new tab</a></div>
<figcaption><p>The design of the extrinsic evaluation</p></figcaption></figure><p>The two experts’ responses were combined to create a reference
standard as follows: (1) if a finding was eliminated by both experts, it
was eliminated in the reference standard; (2) if a finding was eliminated
by one expert but kept by the other, we generated a random number
to decide if it should be eliminated. We then compared the eliminations
done by the system with the reference standard. Each finding eliminated
by the system was classified either as (1) “true negative” (TN), if
it was also eliminated from the reference; or as (2) “false
negative” (FN), if it was kept by the reference. Similarly, each
finding kept by the system was classified either
as (1) “true positive” (TP), if it was also kept by the
reference; or as (2) “false positive” (FP), if was
not kept by the reference.</p>
<p>Two metrics were used to assess system performance for each discharge summary: (1) sensitivity (defined as how often “non-redundant” terms
were kept.) and (2) specificity (defined as how well “redundant” terms were eliminated.).</p></section><section id="sec10"><h2 class="pmc_sec_title">4. Results</h2>
<section id="sec11"><h3 class="pmc_sec_title">4.1 The co-occurrence data</h3>
<p>Overall co-occurrence data are summarized in <a href="#t2-amia2005_0106" class="usa-link">Table 2</a>. 2201 co-occurrence pairs were selected by χ<sup>2</sup> statistics and 3234 pairs were selected by the PCI method. The two sets
shared 848 associations. These two sets were used to construct the knowledge
bases KB-χ<sup>2</sup> and KB-PCI. In KB-χ<sup>2</sup>, 2201 disease-finding associations were implemented as 366 entries. In
KB-PCI, there were 163 entries constructed from 3234 disease-finding
associations. Example knowledge base entries are illustrated in <a href="#t3-amia2005_0106" class="usa-link">Table 3</a>.</p>
