</table></div>
<div class="p text-right font-secondary"><a href="table/t6-amia2005_0106/" class="usa-link" target="_blank" rel="noopener noreferrer">Open in a new tab</a></div></section></section></section><section id="sec14"><h2 class="pmc_sec_title">5. Discussion</h2>
<p>This study establishes that the use of co-occurrence statistics is a simple, feasible
approach to mine a clinical data warehouse for disease-finding
associations. In a parallel exercise, this technique could be
used for discovering disease-disease associations, disease-procedure associations, disease-medication associations, and other interesting associations. Our
approach did not look at the context in which disease
terms and finding terms occur, but simply at their direct co-occurrences. The
simplicity of this approach is counterbalanced by the fact that
its statistics are based on a very large corpus. We speculate that to
discover associations for a target disease, disease context might play
a more important role.</p>
<p>In this study, we used an NLP tool, MedLEE to extract disease and finding
terms from the text. There are two major benefits of using NLP. First, MedLEE
normalizes the words and phrases in the source text and increases
the accuracy of term extraction. Second, it recognizes multi-word
phrases with a high level of accuracy. However, the major disadvantage
of an NLP system is that it can only extract the terms that are defined
in its lexicon, a component used for lexical lookup (a crucial step
for extracting information). The MedLEE lexicon does not cover a large
number of medical terms. There are only 1987 disease terms and 739 finding
terms defined in this lexicon. Because we only extracted the
co-occurrence pairs of the defined terms, the discovered associations
are also limited to those possible within the defined terms. We expect
that more associations would be discovered with a larger covering lexicon.</p>
<p>With respect to our application of volume tests, the 85<sup>th</sup> percentile was an empirical cutoff for associations. When examining the
associations between the 85<sup>th</sup> percentile and 96<sup>th</sup> percentile in our data, 38% of them were found to be false associations (data
not shown), demonstrating that an empirical statistical
cutoff is not completely ideal for our situation. We used the stricter 96<sup>th</sup> percentile to ensure a higher magnitude of associations and achieved a
much higher level of accuracy (97%). Experimenting with the cutoff
thresholds from 85<sup>th</sup> to 96<sup>th</sup> percentile on a small training set and assessing the disease-finding pairs
obtained might shed more light on determining an optimal cutoff value
allowing for the inclusion of maximal true associations with sufficient
accuracy. In future studies, our calibration technique for determining
the optimal cutoff point will use <em>p</em>-value plots carried on the adjusted <em>p</em>-values obtained from volume tests.</p>
<p>Our intrinsic evaluation showed that a proportion of obtained associations
were indirect associations. One interesting example is “myasthenia
gravis” and “cushingoid facies”. It is
considered to be an indirect association because cushingoid facies are
caused by glucocorticoids, which are a treatment for myasthenia gravis
rather than a direct manifestation of the disease itself. As a further
line of research, it would be desirable to develop a means to distinguish
between direct and indirect associations. More sophisticated
statistical models should be explored to achieve this goal.</p>
<p>The χ<sup>2</sup> statistics and PCI method are based on different premises. The former
selects the most significant associations; whereas the latter selects
the findings that are common for a disease. Therefore the two knowledge
bases would be expected to be somewhat different and complementary. It
is not surprising that they share only 848 associations (38.5% of
KB-χ<sup>2</sup> and 26.2% of KB-PCI). Furthermore, in the intrinsic evaluation, we
observed that a significant portion of the associations in KB-χ<sup>2</sup> were disease-specific findings. We hypothesize that KB-χ<sup>2</sup> has the potential to assist linking specific findings to diseases, which
will be a subject of our future studies.</p></section><section id="sec15"><h2 class="pmc_sec_title">7. Conclusion</h2>
<p>This study demonstrates that co-occurrence statistics can be effectively
used to find disease-finding associations hidden in a clinical data
warehouse. Both χ<sup>2</sup> statistics and the PCI method can offer a useful estimation of independence
on the co-occurrences for association selection.</p></section><section id="ack1" class="ack"><h2 class="pmc_sec_title">Acknowledgments</h2>
<p>8. Acknowledgements</p>
<p>This study was funded by grant LM06910 from the National Library of Medicine, Bethesda, Maryland.</p></section><section id="ref-list1" class="ref-list"><h2 class="pmc_sec_title">References</h2>
